\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid9589514 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 
\par I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was there much employment around in the time before the first war?
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid9589514 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well there must have been 
work. But work was bad because - as far as I can gather the tailoring - was always a poor trade. The boot trade was always a poor trade. The reason why because it was seasonable. For every season, you had different trades. You never had gown shops like yo
u have now. You used to go to a dressmaker. Go to a shop, there used to be big - linen draper shops, such as Wickham\rquote s, then my mother always used to deal to Owen\rquote s. And - she\rquote 
d buy rolls and rolls of material, because she had a lot of girls, and she used to take it to a dressmaker, we were all measured for frocks you see. Or else granny would - get something to cut - somebody to cut out something and she\rquote 
d sit and stitch. You see, work - work was - hard to come by. And you still couldn\rquote t get - work if you - if you - weren\rquote 
t dressed properly. I always say to be poor and to look poor is a very very bad thing. Because if you used to go after a job - and you didn\rquote t look decent, they\rquote d look at you and say - got no room for you. But if you put on a brass face and 
you\rquote re dressed properly, and you go in, you know, with that - yes, they\rquote ll take you. But they used to stick bills out, so and so wanted, so and so wanted. But when the men used to go after it they didn\rquote 
t want it, see, putting these sort of bills out used t
o take the feel of the trade. And these governors, in any trade - would know exactly what was doing, because the first thing they say to a man, where was the last place that you worked at? What were you getting? See, and this is how work went. It went in 
seasons. And I\rquote ve known the time when my husband\rquote s come home and he says to me, I\rquote ve got a job, and I said, oh that\rquote s good. But two weeks before Easter he\rquote 
s come home with his cards, they just wanted that little bit of work quick that they take anyone on, you see. And - to get that work out, and after they got that work out then you get the push. You get your cards. And that\rquote s how it was years ago.

\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid9589514 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did your father have many people working for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 My father? At one time he had working for him - he had - twenty barrows, and he employed people - to go out for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 This is in addition to the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh yes. But then, \lquote course then that got too much for him, he couldn\rquote t - see to it, but - he sold them out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 When was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh - about 1916, 1917. See.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 So it was quite a big concern he was running?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Yes. YES. And I\rquote ve known my father to tell me - before he had the shop, he\rquote s walked from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - to Epsom to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, to sell - ice cream. To sell hokey - pokeys, well you know what I mean by hokey-pokey\rquote s? It\rquote 
s this strawberry - and vanilla ice cream - wrapped up in paper, you know like you get the wafers now, but this was in the white - pure white paper, all cut - cut in blocks. And you put it in a freezer, and they\rquote d walk - the m
en with him would walk to Epsom. And if they sold out then they could ride home. But if they didn\rquote t sell out they had to walk home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Is that about twenty odd miles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well, you know where Epsom racing is today. It\rquote s a good - a good distance. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was your father very interested in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
The only sport that my father ever liked was boxing. He used to love a good boxing match. Yes. If it was clean. And we used to have wonderful customers come into the shop. Now we did have one customer - it was a Lord Tredegar\rquote 
s nephew, a Mr Llewellyn. And - he told my father he\rquote d paid ten guineas - for a ringside seat. And he fight was over in a second, the first blow knocked the fellow out. Oh dear. Well - my father used to speak the old English. And - 
we were laughing upstairs today. About the way father used to talk. He didn\rquote t - used to say I heard that, he\rquote 
d say, heared that. See? And - you know, funny thing, and I - as we said this afternoon - if my father was - should be - happened to be eating, and anyone came in, father\rquote 
s first words were - will you join me? And the answer used to be - no thank you, much can I do you. Now listen what I\rquote m saying. Much good may it do you. So they used to - say it so quick, much may I do you. Well I tell you, I was re
ading a book - on one occasion, and I read this word - I thought to myself, what does that mean? I\rquote 
ve heard father say that. And then - in brackets, much good may - and I sat here and I laughed, I thought, well - father - now I know what you were talking about. And we were - that\rquote 
s what we were laughing at - upstairs - this afternoon. Much good may it do you. Much good - it took - it took us a long time to find out what that meant. And there\rquote s so many other words that I hear sometimes with the people that -
 is in the Lane, the old fashioned English people. And there\rquote s only a few of \lquote em left. But when they all meet, and you hear all these old words, you think back, you think to yourself, oh that\rquote 
s father used to say - say that. See? But we got - had a good laugh over that, much good may it do you. Took a lifetime - as I say, it took a lifetime for me to find out what that was. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was he ever a member of any societies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Only the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
orresters. That - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028  was a sick society. That was a sick society, bu
t he never drew a penny. He never - thank goodness he never went sick. I think on one occasion - he\rquote d had a cold and he thought he would go sick. And of course in the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028 se}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028  days they were very very hot - on people. If you were sick and you went to your doctor - you couldn\rquote 
t walk about unless you got a - what they call a walking voucher. A walking voucher to allow you out a certain time in the morning to a certain time in the afternoon. But if - these societies used to send a visitor round and you were out after
 that certain time - you was off the sick.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 You\rquote d lose your benefit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Yes. And I can remember my father saying, only once did he ever go sick because he had a - like a carbuncle on the back of his neck. You know what I mean by a carbuncle? You don\rquote t? You do? Yes. A - a collection of boils. And he\rquote 
d gone to the doctor. And the doctor told him - he was eating the wrong bread - bread.; And my father said, I was born here. And I hope to die here. And he said, and white bread - I\rquote ve always eaten. And w
hite bread I shall die eating. And the doctor said, you\rquote re eating the wrong colour bread, you want to eat the brown. He said, never. And he never did. And my father used to like the hot bread straight from the oven - oven. He\rquote 
d break it open, he\rquote d put a blob of butter in between, and he\rquote d crunch - it had to be crusty, and he\rquote d crunch that and he\rquote d enjoy that better than anything - all the luxury in the world. This is what he used to enjoy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. No. I don\rquote t know 
what - used to go in the way of cakes. Because years ago - what I could gather - at the top there used to be in the open Mile End Road there used to be a - a b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 kers shop that used to take in the big trays - of cakes, you see. And I think for tuppence, they\rquote d bake them you see. But really and truly - the baking was marvellous years ago. They didn\rquote t buy - they didn
\rquote t buy - must - they must have baked because they didn\rquote t buy much shop stuff. The only thing that my father used to buy - or my mother used to buy - was pastries. And they used to come from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Stoney Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, his cousin\rquote s shop, Silver\rquote s. And you used to get twelve beautiful pastries. For a shilling. And then father used to say - tell him you want the baker\rquote 
s dozen, and that was thirteen. See? And they were
 beautiful pastries. And - father always liked - a drop of whisky in the place. So that when his friends or relatives came in, you see, that was always there. And I can remember - when I was fourteen, I left school on the Friday, on the seventeenth of May
 I left school, and I went to work - over at Morris\rquote s here in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mansell Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. It used to be a cigar place. And mind you I only worked - barely two weeks there. But when I used to come out of Morris\rquote s, father used to say to me - in the morning, take this jar, it used to be a stone jar, with a handle. He\rquote 
d put it in one of his big peg bags, and say, take that to work with you, and when you come out of work go into Coate\rquote s, that was a big distillers - in the Whitechapel Road, here, and get a quart of the best s
cotch whisky, for seven shillings. That was three and six a pint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did he often have people coming round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh - always - always had friends. And father could sit all night playing cards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 When would he find time to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 When - if - if friends came in - he\rquote d say all right, I\rquote ll come at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}}ten o\rquote clock{\*\xmlclose}. See? And if he closed at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 10}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}}ten o\rquote clock{\*\xmlclose}, his friends would settle down - to a game of cards, solo, he could play it all night. They\rquote d have the whisky.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where would they play, in the parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 In the shop parlour. The shop -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 There were two parlours were there, the shop parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
No, the parlour upstairs - was for - like weekends when friends and family used to come. But for his friends he used to sit in the shop parlour. It wa
s a nice size room. We had a table - and a few chairs, he had a nice fire - fireplace in. My father was one for fires. I\rquote ve known in - in - looks like its raining, there\rquote s an umbrella up - I\rquote ve known a time then when father - said it
\rquote s chilly in June and he\rquote s lit the fire, he\rquote s had a big fire. And then he\rquote s gone and stood in the shop because it got so hot. See? But he - he used to love warmth. But father would play all night cards. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Would your mother ever join in on those card games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. No. No, card games, them days, was only for men. For men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What other kind of things would your mother and father do to amuse themselves when they weren\rquote t working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well, mother always had plenty to do, although mother was only a young woman when she,
 died, mother was only fifty when she died. See? But - with granny and my elder sisters you see, they all - helped. See? But - there wasn\rquote t - much that he could do really after that. Because - his partner had gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 He was in partnership was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No, no, mother. Mother died you see. And of course - the boys never played cards. No. And my father never smoked on a Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Why not Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 He was a Jew. He used to say, work, I\rquote ve got to work, I\rquote ve got a big family to keep. But what I don\rquote 
t have to do I don\rquote t do. And he never allowed my brothers - to smoke either. He used to say, this is your day - that you don\rquote t do. Because in them days - you didn\rquote 
t work on a Saturday. This was the idea I think - when they used to say - well, with the - for the Jewish people, they don\rquote 
t work Saturdays. Then Sunday they can open the shop. Now my father opened Saturday and Sunday. There was only one day a year that he would close - and that was the day of Atonement. The day of the Fast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 When\rquote s that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Round about September time. And if he closed his shop early - on the afternoon before - all the King\rquote s horses he wouldn\rquote 
t have served you. That was that day of Atonement. And that was it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 That was the only day of the year the shop was shut?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What about Bank Holidays, did he not shut?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. Was always open. Always open.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did you have Bank Holidays and things in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No, he used to like going racing. And then it was only - and then it was only either the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ascot{\*\xmlclose}. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ascot{\*\xmlclose} races that he would like to go to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was he a betting man at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Not much. Not much. He - he\rquote d have a flutter. But - he used to say, I\rquote ve got to work too hard to get my money. And I\rquote 
ve got plenty to do with it, see. But - no, gambling didn\rquote t - attract him very much. And if for instance he\rquote d had a - bet, and it come off, he\rquote d say, well I\rquote ll play that up, and after that then I don\rquote 
t spend no more of my money. See, he got to - and I think I\rquote m the same. I\rquote m a bad gambler. Show you what\rquote s happened. Sitting here Saturday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 You said your father was a member of a sick club, was he a member of a boot club or a savings club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 He was a wonderful - organiser of - a loan club. A Christmas club. And - they always used to say 
that - and the customers used to bring money in to him - for so many shares - and every week, I think it used to be on a Saturday evening, in New Road down here, there used to be a public house, and - my sisters and my brothers used to go and pay this mon
ey in. And Christmastime it was a glorious time when it all got paid out. Yes. Christmastime was wonderful. Everybody got their}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
money. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did you celebrate Christmas yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh we always celebrated Christmas. Father - father - always had a turkey. We never knew any different. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Turkey{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Christmastime, yes. Recognised thing. He\rquote d buy it alive. He used to like to see his poultry alive. Then he\rquote 
d take it to the killers. The same with us. In my married life for instance, my brother - he\rquote s dead now,
 but my brother and sister-in-law, my friend and her husband, my husband and myself used to be six of us, Christmas Eve - used to get on the bus and go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Smithfield{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And we\rquote d all come home with turkeys. And twenty-five pounders at that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did you have many people round at Christmas in the old days or would you have it just with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Family. But in my married life - see - it used to be a family gathering. At my in-laws. But dinner - Christmas dinner I always liked in my own place. But - Christmas - evening - we always had together, and Boxing evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What about before the first world war? Would you go out over the Christmas period to peoples houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No, we had people come in - to celebrate Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What kind of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Friends. You see, having a big family - all their friends used to come in. The same as my in-law. All the girls there, and the boys, and the boys at that time used to - go dancing and all that you see. They\rquote 
d bring in girl friends, bring in girl - boy f
riends, and we used to have a real - well, when we lived in Aberavon Road - they - see my - mother-in-law had a piano, and they - used to say, go on Anne, get on the piano. Well it used to be a recognised thing, Sunday afternoon and Christmastimes, we use
d
 to go - we used to be all night. They used to be all night affairs. And we all used to club together - to get the food, and the drink. And from the public house that we used to buy the beer - they used to let us have forms. So that we used to get rid of 
all the chairs and used to put forms all round. Used to have real good times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was this the same in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well I don\rquote t know because we were in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Even on Christmas does?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Yes, we had to go to bed because - father Christmas was coming and if we were up we\rquote re not - he wouldn\rquote 
t come. You see, this was a good gag years ago. But today you can\rquote t do it so easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What about Christmas Day itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh it was lovely, Christmas Day. And the decorations, it was lovely, really lovely. And the toys that we used to get Christmas Eve, we
\rquote d sit and play for hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 You\rquote d get them on Christmas Eve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Yes, we used to hang our stockings up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 You mean you\rquote d hang them up and get them on the Christmas Day itself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh, they 
used to be at the foot of the bed. All our names on our stocking. A few dates used to be stuck at the foot. Oh used to have everything. Yes, used to have lovely Christmases. Games and toys you know, everything like that. All stuck in the stockings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Would you ever go anywhere on Boxing Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Well Boxing Day was a - more - of like a leisure day, you know what I mean, you were tired from the Christmas festivities - of Christmas night, so you practically was - lazy - Boxing Day. And you never cooked B
oxing Day, because you had the remainder of your turkey and your beef, you see, for lunch, and for your supper. And when the friends used to come back - for the evening, there was another celebration. And this is how it used to go. See? Christmastime was 
l
ovely, and it used to be - I can remember as a child - that we used to go round look - 'cos father always decorated up And he used to have the most wonderful decorations. And he was a man that used to take care of his things. That when he used to take the
m down, you know, he\rquote d dust them all and put them all back, put all the chains back properly, and all the bells and all the birds and everything, he\rquote d put \lquote em all away, stack \lquote en all in a pot - in a box, and tuck \lquote 
em all in with a blue tissue paper and put \rquote em up on a shelf, he said, they\rquote re ready for next year. Always. And we used to go round to different shops, and we\rquote 
d say, oh look at this. The same as Guy Fawkes night. See, they - they were the days that - we used to celebrate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where would you go for Guy Fawkes night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Well we always had a bonfire in the yard and we used to have friends in. And when I got married - we had a bonfire in the garden, and we had friends in, and my - tenants, with their children they used to come down and I used to do
 on - guy Fawkes night, I used to roast potatoes in their Jackets, now you know what I mean? Used to scrub the potatoes up, and pop \lquote em in the oven, so while we\rquote were having - enjoying ourselves outside - we\rquote 
ve got these - potatoes cooking, so that when they - of course it\rquote 
s November, everybody come in cold and miserable, we used to stick a fork - through these potatoes and used to split them, put vinegar and salt on, and the - all the kids used to - well we used to enjoy it ourselves, we were grown ups, and
 the children used to enjoy it you see. And have a hot drink, and then - they we used to go to bed. And that was - Guy Fawkes night. But I always used to say, no fireworks \lquote 
til Guy Fawkes night. See? And - the boys used to save their money. I used to go with them to buy what they want, but it was only the day before. Buy Fawkes day. Not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 When you were young would you play more with your brothers and sisters than you\rquote d play with neighbours children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well we all played together. We - we all - we w
ere all allowed to have a friend in, you see. And of course as I say there was a lot of us, there was three - three - four young ones. See, my sister, this one. And - three others. You see. And - holiday time we used to be over Victoria Park. Our friends 
used to come as well. See? We were - we were no nuisance to any neighbour. In fact -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Would you play indoors more when it wasn\rquote t holiday time, or where would you go to play when it wasn\rquote 
t holiday time, you said you weren\rquote t allowed in the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 We weren\rquote 
t in the street, we had our back yard. Yes, or else if it was wet we used to be downstairs. You see. And as I say the servant used to put on little plays for us for the weekend. Then the - other boy, we used to get - one Sunday - night over in ou
r place. You see, and - the following Sunday this boy - he\rquote s a stone rich man now, he used to do the magic lanterns. And he used to tell us stories. Don\rquote 
t know what - what he used to make up. But he used to relate stories, to us what he was showing, the slides that he was - used to be glass slides with little teeny pictures on it, used to put through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Would he come round or would you go to his place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 We\rquote d go to his, because - he had a place where he could put the sheet up on the wall you see. And
 we had the servant used to play love in the sack. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 She\rquote d make you do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No, she\rquote d do it. Shed do it. And she\rquote d recite poetry. And then we\rquote 
d all have to - say a nursery rhyme, I was saying rhymes - Monday over in this launderette to a l
ittle girl. She said to me, do you know - Humpty-Dumpty? I said, yes. She looked at me. And a woman from round the back, she come and sat in front, she said, golly, she said, it\rquote s years since I\rquote ve heard that. I said, well they don\rquote 
t teach the children these things today. Nursery rhymes, yes, Humpty-Dumpty. I said to this little girl, do you know Wee Willie Winkle? Oh yes, she said, I do. I said, do you know Miss Muffet? Oh, she couldn\rquote 
t think about Miss Muffet so I told her Miss Muffet, and - Little Jack Ho
rner. I said, you see, this used to be how we used to pass our time. Then there were certain games. You see this book, we never had books like this. We never had books like this. But used to have a newspaper, for one ha\rquote 
penny. A newspaper used to cost a ha\rquote penny. And used to be pictures. Well we\rquote d save these pictures, we cut them out, and then we\rquote d get a big book, a thick book and we\rquote d put all these pictures in different pages, and we\rquote 
d start singing, when our friends was all in - we\rquote d start singing - a pin
, a pick, a jolly good pick. Why? Why was it a pin a pick? Because we all had pin cushions and when granny was making things she wanted pins - for pinning the - things together. So she used to say, cut out some pictures and put \lquote 
em in a book and go and - g
o and play, pin a pick. See, well we used to give granny the pins. And - all these - this - these were our games, and then - used to come a time when the boys used to have marbles. And their peg tops. And their whip tops. The girls used to have - gobs and
 bomsters when we used to sit on the kerb. Well we wasn\rquote t - as I say, we wasn\rquote t allowed in the street so we\rquote d sit in the yard, on the step, and we\rquote d have the children in and we\rquote 
d play these gobs and bomsters, you know. And we\rquote d have ball. We\rquote d have a game wally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Throw the ball against the wall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Yes. And of course we didn\rquote t have much room to run in-the yard. Or else we\rquote 
d play off ground - off ground touch. You see. Skipping. For the girls. Every season bought its own games. Then the boys used to h
ave a game of buttons. A boy used to take his cap off and put it in the street and another boy had to stand, say by the kerb, and had to throw an button, but he had to have his own button, you see, and throw it. If he got \lquote 
em in the cap - that was his back again. But if he didn\rquote t, whatever fell on the floor was the one that - cap belonged to. Used to be murders over that. Murders over that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where did he get his buttons from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well I suppose their - everybody had buttons. I\rquote ve got a box of buttons here now. A huge big box of buttons I\rquote 
ve got here, I keep \lquote em. If anybody - anybody says, here, have you got any buttons, I say, I\rquote ve got plenty of buttons but I don\rquote t know if it\rquote s the colour you want.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 How did you get the servant in the first place, did you advertise or was it somebody local or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Servant? Oh we advertised, put a bill in the window, the side window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did you know her before she moved in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. But - the servant always had a room on her own. See? And - my aunt as well had a servant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What hours did she work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well she was - always there. You see, that\rquote s why I say a servant\rquote s job\rquote 
