Oh my God, I tell you, I was only a - youngster - when she - left to get married. I must have been about - nine years old when she got - left to get married, and she recognised me. And she was living i
n the next turning to me. And she said, who have you got to do your work? Oh I said, Lizzie, I do it myself. She said, you weren\rquote t brought up that way. I said, it doesn\rquote t matter Lizze. I said, I do it. She said, I\rquote 
ll come and do it for you. I said, no thanks Lizzie, I said, I\rquote ll carry on myself. My husband was out of work. But when I told her - so she said, I don\rquote t want any payment, she said, for old time\rquote s sake she said I\rquote 
ll come and work for you. It\rquote s the same as - as - a Jessie Barnet lives over there in
 Lullsworth buildings. She was a servant to my sister-in-law. And she run away from my sister-in-law and she came to me. I said, Jessie, I would willingly have you. She said, let me stop here with you. She said, I\rquote 
ll do all your work. I said, look Jessie, I couldn\rquote t take you like that. My sister-in-law would accuse me of taking you. I said, but if you want to stay here you can stay, but I said I\rquote ve got no money to pay you. She said, I\rquote 
ll work for you for nothing. I said, but I don\rquote t - wouldn\rquote t want you to work for me for nothing. See? Nobody - nobody\rquote 
s entitled to work for nothing. You see, and this is it. And she only lives over there. And many a time she used to say to me - oh - I always wanted to come and live with you. I used to say, yes, but it couldn\rquote t
 be. See? Yes, times - times was hard. See I had hard times when I got married. I think that's John - ticking the kids off. Yes. I - I had times when I got married for the simple reason - my husband -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What year did Lizzie leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Don\rquote t know, I must have been about nine years old.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Before your mother died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Yes, just before my mother died. She left to get married you see, and - then we had Mrs Lincoln, a char lady. She used to come in from Mondays to Fridays, regularly. Clockwork. And - m
y mother died in 1912. Now before 19 - before that - Lloyd George brought in this scheme for the - National insurance. And - Mrs Lincoln had to pay - I think forpence a week, and father had to pay the other fivepence. I think the stamp at that time was ni
nepence. Insurance. 1912. That was just before my mother died, my mother died 1912. And Mrs Lincoln was carrying on - she said her husband didn\rquote t think it right that she should have fivepence stopped. My father said well I\rquote 
ve got to - fourpence stopped - father said, well I\rquote ve got to pay fivepence. See? The stamp was ninepence. And I think you were entitled to - sick benefit. I don\rquote t - I - I - of course I don\rquote t remember m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8153771\charrsid6362028 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 ch about that. But - there it is. That I can remember. And - years after - she had two 
children. Years after when I first went to the blind club from the Tower Hamlets, I became a registered person for the blind club, and they took me to Key Close. Now Key Close is along Mile End - Road where the Assembly Halls - the Assembly Hall is, it
\rquote s like a church place see. And there\rquote s - there were at the time, old sailors cottages. And I used to go through there to this - big place. Key Close - bought you out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cambridge Heath Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well I never knew my way round that way, in fact I was taken so I - I didn\rquote 
t know, I was taken to - that entrance and we used to walk through. Now - funnily enough - when I walked in, there was a man and a woman sitting there. And the woman got up and she come over to me, she said - you\rquote re Hannah? I said, yes. So she said
, do you recognise me? I said, no. She said, I\rquote m Mary Anne Lincoln. I said, good gracious me. She said, and this is my husband. See, he was blind. And she\rquote d come as a guide to him. And it was this very char woman\rquote 
s - daughter, youngest daughter, from all them years ago and she recognised me. See? It\rquote s funny you know. Funny how things work out and come out. You don\rquote t know who you meet in the course of a lifetime. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What about Lizzie, did you just call her Lizzie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 We called her Lizzie. Lizzie Cabl
e was her name. What we used to say, Lizzie Cable sat on a table, the table went pop and Lizzie went flop. Oh I remember that we used to say. And she used to start us off, she used to say, come on now, Lizzie Cable sat on the table. And we used to say it.
 Kiddyish voice. Lizze Cable sat on the table, the went flop - the table went pop and Lizzie went flop. She used to say, yes, now you can have a sweet. See? That\rquote s how we used to spend our time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What would she call your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Mrs. And sir. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did your mother ever give any moral guidance to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 To who?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Lizzie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh that I don\rquote t know. That I don\rquote 
t know. I remembrance - I remember once - she went with a man. The one that she married, and he was in a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mile End Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, housed to sell - all these gardening tools. And Lizzie had taken us along {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mile End Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, \lquote cos there was wonderful shops along 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mile End Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at the time - and she was talking to this man. And when she came home, I remember her saying to my mother -
 everything is fixed up, and I\rquote ll be leaving you. And my mother said, you\rquote re leaving? She said, yes, \lquote cos I\rquote m going to get married. Always remember that. But as regards guidance I don\rquote t know. Couldn\rquote t say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did Lizzie give you baths and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No, no, there was my mother. No. Oh no, she never had anything like that to do with us like that, not with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What kind of things would she do then, just general housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 The housework, yes, and see that - the table was laid properly and - all chairs was all polished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 She\rquote d take you for walks, you say you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Greenwich
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with her, but would she take you for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 She\rquote d take - yes, but then father used to give her a - giver her her fare, our fares. You see, and she - we u
sed to ride to Greenwich - and coming through Blackwall Tunnel last week, last Monday - I said, this always puts me in mind - I don\rquote 
t like tunnels, this puts me in mind, I said, of Greenwich, when our servant used to take us to Greenwich and I used to be terrified because - there was water. I don\rquote 
t know now if it was water underneath our feet, but do you know, through that very thing I don\rquote t like piers. I - I - I - I go on a pier with a - with a bad heart. And if for instance - from the blind club we go to Brighton, I hate 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}. And we have to go on a pier, I\rquote m terrified. I don\rquote t like it, from - all them years ago, I just don\rquote t like the water under my feet. I\rquote 
m sorry but - they say, well it won\rquote t hurt you. But I don\rquote t like it. And I\lquote m always frightened - I remember once I was at Southend and - to oblige the kids I go on the train, on the pier. I don\rquote 
t know about the kids hanging on for dear life, I know I hung on for dear life, and I swore never - never in me lifetime will I ever go again. And I haven\rquote t. I don\rquote t like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Did you ever go for holidays with your parents?
