\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Was that with your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. From like a school we used to go to, we used to get one days outing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where would you go for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Theydon Bois.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where\rquote s that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Chingford way. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Epping Forest{\*\xmlclose}
. And then we used to go round to all - all our brothers and sisters, all the aunts and uncles to collect. Used to get a penny each. We thought - we used to think we were Lady Rothschild\rquote 
s. Yes. But we always bought mother a present back. And our warning was - when we were going out, now don\rquote t you spend your money foolishly in bringing anything back home. But that\rquote s the first thing 
we did. The gipsies used to come - be there with all the big baskets, all little knick-knacks. And we always used to buy something for mother. And she used to prize it. The same as what I always prize everything that my boys bought me. See? And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 It\rquote s natural to buy things when you go away somewhere isn\rquote t it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Well you want to. You see. But this was our warning, don\rquote 
t you bring anything back. But we did - always. And - well my granddaughter went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} last week, and I gave her ten shillings. 
In fact I give her five shillings each week, but I gave her ten shillings \lquote cos she was going. And she said to me on Sunday - she said, I had a nice day at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} gran. So I said, did you, that\rquote s good, did you enjoy it? So she said, yes. I said, what did you go on? She said, I didn\rquote t go on half of what I wanted, I didn\rquote 
t have sufficient money. I think she went out with three pounds, for spending. She said now - I said, well if you never have more than for that for spending - I said, you still didn\rquote t have mo
ney for the shows that you wanted to go on. She said, we went on the - scenic railway, and we went here and we went there. I said, did you go in to Dreamland? Because I didn\rquote t think Dreamland was there at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} anymore. It\rquote s more like a leisure place. You know, fun - and all that. So I said to her, did you go in the - house, with all funny mirrors? She said, I didn\rquote 
t have sufficient money. I said, I\rquote ll cry for you. So she said she went into the - haunted house. That I didn\rquote t like \lquote cos the floor used to go away from under my feet, only went in that once. No. I\rquote 
m a coward at heart. I like terra firma.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 So you didn\rquote t really go many places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 No. We never had any holidays, no. And that\rquote s why when I grew up I was determined that my boys would have holid
ays. And - I used to pay in for country holiday fund. Couldn\rquote t afford to take them myself. See? But I used to send them away from the school. Country Holiday Fund. And that was the - either the first two weeks of their month\rquote 
s holiday, or the last two weeks. Well I used to give \lquote 
em the last two weeks, because it was still fresh in their memories - for going back to school. Because when you got back to school you had to write about your holidays. See? You had to write a dictation - about your - holidays. And
 I used to think to myself, well that\rquote s the best - the first two weeks I can put up with them. But this is how I used to work it, I used to say - you help me - and then I\rquote 
ll take you out for the afternoon. But any - used to queue up for hours. But it wasn\rquote t a continuous performance. There were certain houses. You see. Until -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What kind of films would they have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Oh - cowboy pictures, and - they used to have serials. And you know - we - he used - if he used to go on a Sunday - to the fair, picture
s for a penny, and we used to see Pearl White, and she\rquote d be hanging to the to the roof of a train by her teeth. And another train\rquote s coming through, we\rquote 
re all cringing, and then it would come up on the sheet, next week - you see, you see the continuation next week. And we were all - tensed up you know. And - Harold Lloyd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 What day of the week would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Well it - any day you could go, for a penny. And over this fair for a penny. Mr Forest, he was a big burly man, and he always lived in a caravan. And it was a most beautiful thing that I\rquote 
d ever seen. See, and father used to serve him with stuff, and father used to say - you take the order over to Mr Forest and ask him to let you go through that caravan. This is a thing that you want to see. They
 had bedrooms. They had a most magnificent steel cooker. They had everything there that a house could have. In these caravans. One caravan was kept for - sitting and eating. And the other caravans, I think there was three in the grounds, were bedrooms. 
\lquote Cos he too had a big family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9589514 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 Where was this now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16539070 HM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3412272\charrsid6362028 
Over in the fair. You know Mile End station? At the back of Mile End station was known as the fairground. During the winter there was all sideshows, but - Mr Forest had this - first of all he used t
o go under a tent. They used to call it the fleat pit. Used to be a ha\rquote 
penny. But when he had it built it was a penny. See, and you used to go in, and you used to get a card. And - and it was a lucky number. If you had a lucky number on it - you either won
 boots or a sack of coal - or - you know, some - articles of clothing. See, the - what this man used to buy for prizes. And it used to be chock-block full. And used to sit on forms. And although it was chock-block full they\rquote 
d still say, come on, shift up there, shift up there, we were all huddled together and when we used to get these serial pictures you know - and the hair raising stuff that they used to do - we\rquote 
d all cringe and cringe and cringe, and the kids - and - and people at the back used to say, look behind, look behind, he\rquote s behind the door, he\rquote 
s behind - of course it used to be silent pictures. Look behind the door. And then it used to come up, continuation next week. And we\rquote d say - aaaah. Will you come next week, will you come next week? Yes, if 
we can save our farthings. We used to get a farthing a day - for spending.
